✅ What is Recursion?
Recursion is a programming technique where a function calls itself to solve a problem by breaking it into smaller subproblems of the same type.

Every recursive solution must have:
Base case → condition to stop recursion
Recursive case → function calls itself with smaller input

In short:
👉 Solve big problem → reduce it → solve smaller → stop at base case

✅ What are Types of Recursion?
Recursion can be classified based on how and where the function calls itself.

1️⃣ Direct Recursion
A function calls itself directly.

Definition:
Function A() calls A() inside its body.

📌 When to use:
When a problem can be solved by calling the same logic repeatedly on smaller input.

Example:
void fun(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    System.out.println(n);
    fun(n - 1);   // direct recursion
}

2️⃣ Indirect Recursion
A function calls another function, which again calls the first function.

Definition:
A → B → A

📌 When to use:
When two or more tasks depend on each other alternately.

Example:
void even(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    odd(n - 1);
}
void odd(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    even(n - 1);
}

3️⃣ Tail Recursion
Recursive call is the last statement in the function.
Nothing is left to execute after the recursive call.

Definition:
All processing is done before recursive call.

📌 When to use:
When:
You just need to repeat work
No extra processing after recursive call
Want better performance & memory usage

Example:
void fun(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    System.out.println(n);
    fun(n - 1);   // last line → tail recursion
}

4️⃣ Head Recursion
Recursive call happens first, before any processing.

Definition:
Processing happens after recursive call returns.

📌 When to use:
When:
You need to process data after going deep
You want output in reverse order
Tree traversal style problems

Example:
void fun(int n) {
    if (n == 0) return;
    fun(n - 1);   // first call
    System.out.println(n);
}

5️⃣ Tree Recursion
Function makes more than one recursive call.

Definition:
One function → multiple recursive calls.

📌 When to use:
When:
One problem splits into multiple subproblems
You explore all possibilities

Example (Fibonacci):
int fib(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2); // two calls
}

6️⃣ Nested Recursion
Recursive call is made inside another recursive call.

Definition:
Function calls itself with a parameter that itself is a recursive call.

📌 When to use:
Rare in real systems.
Used when:
Definition itself is recursive inside recursive call
Academic or tricky problems

Example:
int fun(int n) {
    if (n > 100) return n - 10;
    return fun(fun(n + 11));
}

| Problem Type           | Recursion Type |
| ---------------------- | -------------- |
| Simple repetition      | Direct         |
| Alternating logic      | Indirect       |
| Loop replacement       | Tail           |
| Reverse / Backtracking | Head           |
| Multiple choices       | Tree           |
| Complex math puzzles   | Nested         |
